{{Infobox language |name=Mashco Piro |nativename=Cujareño |states=[[Peru]] |ethnicity=[[Mashco Piro]] |speakers=20–100 |date=1976 |ref=e15<!--E16 to E18 just delete the range--> |familycolor=American |fam1=[[Maipurean languages|Arawakan]] |fam2=Southern |fam3=[[Piro languages|Piro]] |iso3=cuj |glotto=mash1270 |glottorefname=Mashco Piro }}
'''Mashco Puro''' is a [[Maipurean language]] spoken in [[Peru]]. It is also called Cujareño. It is very similar to the [[Piro language (Peru)|Piro]], with an estimated 60% inherent intelligibility.<ref name=e15/> Kaufman considered it a dialect of Piro; Aikhenvald suggests it may rather be a dialect of otherwise extinct [[Iñapari language|Iñapari]].
Language documentation is limited, since the [[Mascho Piro]] are highly nomadic [[hunter-gatherers]]<ref name=e15/> who avoid contact with outsiders. The name Cujareño has been associated with the [[Panoan languages]], though without much evidence.
