{{selfref|For assistance with IPA transcriptions of Slovak for Wikipedia articles, see [[Help:IPA/Slovak]].}} {{IPA notice}} This article is about the [[phonology]] and [[phonetics]] of the [[Slovak language]]. {{Listen|filename=SK-morho.ogg|title=Sample|description= An excerpt of Slovak poem 'Mor ho' by [[Samo Chalupka]] (1812–1883). The speaker is a 21-year-old woman from [[Bratislava]].}}
==Vowels==
===Monophthongs=== [[File:Ranges of Slovak monophthongs.svg|thumb|upright=1.13|Ranges of the standard Slovak monophthongs, from {{Harvcoltxt|Pavlík|2004|p=95}}]] {| class="wikitable" style=text-align:center |+ Slovak [[monophthong]] phonemes{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=375}}{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|p=51}} ! rowspan="2" | ! colspan="2" | [[Front vowel|Front]] ! colspan="2" | [[Back vowel|Back]] |- class=small ! short ! long ! short ! long |- ! align="left" | [[Close vowel|Close]] | align="center" | {{IPA link|i̞|i}} | align="center" | {{IPA link|i̞|iː}} | align="center" | {{IPA link|u̞|u}} | align="center" | {{IPA link|u̞|uː}} |- ! align="left" | [[Mid vowel|Mid]] | align="center" | {{IPA link|ɛ̝|ɛ}} | align="center" | {{IPA link|ɛ̝|ɛː}} | align="center" | {{IPA link|ɔ̝|ɔ}} | align="center" | ({{IPA link|ɔ̝|ɔː}}) |- ! align="left" | [[Open vowel|Open]] | align="center" | ({{IPA link|æ}}) | | align="center" | {{IPA link|ä|a}} | align="center" | {{IPA link|ä|aː}} |}
====Phonetic realization==== * The close and mid vowels are typically peripheral, but they can at times be somewhat centralized.{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|pp=93–95}} * {{IPA|/i, iː, u, uː/}} are typically near-close {{IPA|[{{IPA link|i̞}}, {{IPA link|i̞ː}}, {{IPA link|u̞}}, {{IPA link|u̞ː}}]}}, but sometimes they can be close {{IPA|[{{IPA link|i}}, {{IPA link|iː}}, {{IPA link|u}}, {{IPA link|uː}}]}} instead.{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|pp=93, 95}} * {{IPA|/ɛ, ɛː, ɔ, ɔː/}} are typically mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɛ̝}}, {{IPA link|ɛ̝ː}}, {{IPA link|ɔ̝}}, {{IPA link|ɔ̝ː}}]}}. {{IPA|/ɛ, ɛː/}} are slightly higher than {{IPA|/ɔ, ɔː/}} - this can be transcribed in narrow transcription as {{IPA|[{{IPA link|e̞}}, {{IPA link|e̞ː}}]}} vs. {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɔ̝}}, {{IPA link|ɔ̝ː}}]}}. At times, {{IPA|/ɛ, ɛː/}} can be as close as close-mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|e}}, {{IPA link|eː}}]}} and {{IPA|/ɔ, ɔː/}} as open as open-mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɔ}}, {{IPA link|ɔː}}]}}.{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|pp=94–95}} * Speakers often fail at attempts to pronounce {{IPA|/æ/}}, pronouncing a vowel that is phonetically too close to either {{IPA|/ɛ/}} or {{IPA|/a/}}.{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|p=55}} * {{IPA|/a, aː/}} are typically open central {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ä}}, {{IPA link|äː}}]}}, but at times they can be somewhat fronted {{IPA|[{{IPA link|a|a̠}}, {{IPA link|a|a̠ː}}]}}, retracted {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɑ|ɑ̟}}, {{IPA link|ɑ|ɑ̟ː}}]}} or raised {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɐ}}, {{IPA link|ɐː}}]}}.{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|pp=94–95}} * Under Hungarian influence, some speakers realize {{IPA|/ɛː, ɔː/}} as close-mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|eː}}, {{IPA link|oː}}]}} and {{IPA|/a/}} as open back rounded {{IPAblink|ɒ}}. The close-mid realizations of {{IPA|/ɛː, ɔː/}} occur also in southern dialects spoken near the river [[Ipeľ]].{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|pp=54, 92}}
====Other notes==== * Vowel length is not phonemic in Eastern dialects,{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=375}} which have only five vowel phonemes ({{IPA|/i, u, ɛ, ɔ, a/}}, some speakers also have {{IPA|/æ/}}). * In Western dialects, vowels that are short due to the rhythmical rule{{Explain|date=September 2018}} are often realized as long, and thus violating the rule.{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=376}} * {{IPA|/y, yː, œ, œː, ɔː/}} occur only in loanwords.{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=375}}{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|pp=64–65}} Just as other mid vowels, {{IPA|/œ, œː/}} are phonetically true-mid {{IPA|[{{IPA link|œ̝}}, {{IPA link|œ̝ː}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|p=64}} Among these vowels, only {{IPA|/ɔː/}} is consistently realized in the correct manner, whereas the occurrence of the front rounded vowels {{IPA|/y, yː, œ, œː/}} has been reported only by {{Harvcoltxt|Kráľ|1988}}, who states that the front rounded vowels appear only in the high register and medium register. However, in the medium register, {{IPA|/y, yː/}} and {{IPA|/œ, œː/}} are often either too back, which results in realizations that are phonetically too close to, respectively, {{IPA|/u, uː/}} and {{IPA|/ɔ, ɔː/}}, or too weakly rounded, yielding vowels that are phonetically too close to, respectively, {{IPA|/i, iː/}} and {{IPA|/ɛ, ɛː/}}.{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|pp=57, 64–65, 103}} * {{IPA|/uː, ɛː/}} do not occur after soft consonants, where they are replaced by the corresponding diphthongs {{IPA|/ɪ̯u, ɪ̯ɛ/}}. The same is generally true for {{IPA|/aː/}} ({{IPA|/ɪ̯a/}} after soft consonants), but the sequence {{IPA|/jaː/}} may occur in some cases.{{sfnp|Short|2002|pp=534–535}} * Long {{IPA|/ɛː/}} occurs only in loanwords, one native word (''dcéra'') and in adjective endings.{{sfnp|Short|2002|p=535}} * {{IPA|/æ/}} can only be short, and occurs only after {{IPA|/m, p, b, v/}}.{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=375}}{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|p=55}} There is not a full agreement about its status in the standard language: ** {{Harvcoltxt|Kráľ|1988}} states that the correct pronunciation of {{IPA|/æ/}} is an important part of the high register, but in medium and low registers, {{IPA|/æ/}} merges with {{IPA|/ɛ/}}, or, in some cases, with {{IPA|/a/}}.{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|p=55}} ** {{Harvcoltxt|Short|2002}} states that only about 5% of speakers have {{IPA|/æ/}} as a distinct phoneme, and that even when it is used in formal contexts, it is most often a dialect feature.{{sfnp|Short|2002|p=534}} ** {{Harvcoltxt|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010}} state that the use of {{IPA|/æ/}} is becoming rare, and that it often merges with {{IPA|/ɛ/}}.{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=375}}
===Diphthongs=== {| class="wikitable" style=text-align:center |+ Slovak [[diphthong]] phonemes{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|p=51}}{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=376}} ! rowspan="2" | ! colspan="3" | Ending point |- ! [[Front vowel|Front]] ! [[Central vowel|Central]] ! [[Back vowel|Back]] |- ! Unrounded | {{IPA|ɪ̯ɛ}} | {{IPA|ɪ̯a}} | {{IPA|ɪ̯u}} |- ! Rounded | | | {{IPA|ʊ̯ɔ}} |}
* All of the diphthongs are rising, i.e. their second elements have more prominence.{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=376}}{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|p=95}} * The phonetic quality of Slovak diphthongs is as follows: ** {{IPA|/ɪ̯ɛ/}} is typically a glide from {{IPA|/i/}} to {{IPA|/ɛ/}} ({{IPA|[ȋ̞ɛ̝]}}).{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|pp=96–97}} ** {{IPA|/ɪ̯a/}} is typically a glide from the position below {{IPA|/i/}} to {{IPA|/æ/}} ({{IPA|[ȇ̝æ̠]}}).{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|pp=95, 97}} ** {{IPA|/ɪ̯u/}} is typically a glide from {{IPA|/i/}} to the position more front than {{IPA|/u/}} ({{IPA|[ȋ̞ʊ]}}).{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|pp=96–97}} ** {{IPA|/ʊ̯ɔ/}} is typically a glide from {{IPA|/u/}} to the position above {{IPA|/ɔ/}} ({{IPA|[ȗ̞o̞]}}).{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|pp=96–97}} * There are many more phonetic diphthongs, such as {{IPA|[aʊ̯]}} in ''Miroslav'' {{IPA|[ˈmirɔslaʊ̯]}} and {{IPA|[ɔʊ̯]}} in ''Prešov'' {{IPA|[ˈprɛʃɔʊ̯]}}. Phonemically, these are interpreted as sequences of {{IPA|/v/}} preceded by a vowel. This {{IPA|[ʊ̯]}} is phonetically {{IPA|[ȗ̞]}} and it is very similar to the first element of {{IPA|/ʊ̯ɔ/}}.{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|p=105}}{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}}
==Consonants== {| class="wikitable" style=text-align:center |+ Slovak consonant phonemes{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}} ! colspan="2" | ! [[Labial consonant|Labial]] ! [[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ! [[Postalveolar consonant|Postalveolar]] ! [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ! [[Velar consonant|Velar]] ! [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- ! colspan="2" | [[Nasal consonant|Nasal]] | {{IPA link|m}} | {{IPA link|n}} | | {{IPA link|ɲ}} | | |- ! rowspan="2" | [[Plosive consonant|Plosive]] ! {{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}} | {{IPA link|p}} | {{IPA link|t}} | | {{IPA link|c}} | {{IPA link|k}} | |- ! {{small|[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}} | {{IPA link|b}} | {{IPA link|d}} | | {{IPA link|ɟ}} | {{IPA link|ɡ}} | |- ! rowspan="2" | [[Affricate consonant|Affricate]] ! {{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}} | | {{IPA link|ts}} | {{IPA link|tʂ|tʃ}} | | | |- ! {{small|[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}} | | {{IPA link|dz}} | {{IPA link|dʐ|dʒ}} | | | |- ! rowspan="2" | [[Continuant consonant|Continuant]] ! {{small|[[voicelessness|voiceless]]}} | {{IPA link|f}} | {{IPA link|s}} | {{IPA link|ʂ|ʃ}} | | {{IPA link|x}} | |- ! {{small|[[voice (phonetics)|voiced]]}} | {{IPA|v}} | {{IPA link|z}} | {{IPA link|ʐ|ʒ}} | {{IPA link|j}} | | {{IPA link|ɦ}} |- ! rowspan="2" | [[Lateral consonant|Lateral]] ! {{small|plain}} | | {{IPA link|ɫ|l}} | | {{IPA link|ʎ}} | | |- ! {{small|[[gemination|geminated]]}} | | {{IPA link|ɫ|lː}} | | | | |- ! colspan="2" | [[Tap consonant|Tap]] | | {{IPA link|ɾ|r}}<!-- Please do not change it to "{{IPA link|ɾ}}", we transcribe it as reliable sources do. --> | | | | |- ! colspan="2" | [[Trill consonant|Trill]] | | {{IPA link|r|rː}}<!-- Please do not change it to "{{IPA link|r}}", we transcribe it as reliable sources do. --> | | | | |}
* Voiceless stops and affricates are unaspirated. * Voiced stops and affricates are fully voiced. * {{IPA|/n/}} is [[Apical consonant|apical]] alveolar {{IPAblink|n|n̺}}.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Kráľ|1988|p=73}}. The author describes {{IPA|/n/}} as apical alveolar, but the corresponding image shows a laminal denti-alveolar pronunciation (which he does not discuss).</ref> * {{IPA|/t, d, t͡s, d͡z, s, z, ɲ, c, ɟ/}} are laminal {{IPA|[t̻, d̻, t̻͡s̻, d̻͡z̻, s̻, z̻, ɲ̻, c̻, ɟ̻]}}.{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|pp=72, 74–75, 80–82}} ** {{IPA|/t, d/}} are alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|t}}, {{IPA link|d}}]}} or denti-alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|t̪}}, {{IPA link|d̪}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|p=72}}{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|pp=98–99}} ** {{IPA|/t͡s, d͡z, s, z/}} are alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|t͡s}}, {{IPA link|d͡z}}, {{IPA link|s}}, {{IPA link|z}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|pp=74–75}}{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|pp=103–104}} *** Word-initial {{IPA|/d͡z/}} occurs only in two words: ''dzekať'' and ''dziny''.{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}} ** {{IPA|/c, ɟ, ɲ/}} are [[Alveolo-palatal consonant|alveolo-palatal]] {{IPA|[{{IPA link|c|c̟<sup>ç</sup>}}, {{IPA link|ɟ|ɟ̟<sup>ʝ</sup>}}, {{IPA link|ɲ̟}}]}}.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Dvončová|Jenča|Kráľ|1969|pp=?}}, cited in {{Harvcoltxt|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}}</ref>{{sfnp|Pauliny|1979|p=112}}{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|pp=81–82}}{{sfnp|Recasens|2013|pp=11, 13}} *** As indicated in the transcription, {{IPA|/c, ɟ/}} are weakly affricated.{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|p=80}} *** {{IPA|/ɲ/}} can also be dento-alveolo-palatal.{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|pp=81–82}} * {{IPA|/ʎ/}} is palatalized laminal denti-alveolar {{IPAblink|ʎ|l̪ʲ}},{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|p=82}} palatalized laminal alveolar {{IPAblink|ʎ|l̻ʲ}}{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}}{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|p=82}}{{sfnp|Dvončová|Jenča|Kráľ|1969|pp=94–95}} or palatal {{IPAblink|ʎ}}.{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}}{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|p=82}}{{sfnp|Dvončová|Jenča|Kráľ|1969|pp=94–95}} The palatal realization is the least common one.{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}}{{sfnp|Dvončová|Jenča|Kráľ|1969|pp=94–95}} ** {{Harvcoltxt|Pavlík|2004}} describes an additional realization, namely a weakly palatalized apical alveolar approximant {{IPA|[l̺ʲ]}}. According to this scholar, the palatal realization {{IPA|[ʎ]}} is actually alveolo-palatal {{IPAblink|ʎ̟}}.{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|p=105}} * The {{IPA|/ʎ–l/}} contrast is neutralized before front vowels, where only {{IPA|/l/}} occurs. This neutralization is taken further in western dialects, in which {{IPA|/ʎ/}} merges with {{IPA|/l/}} in all environments.{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}} * {{IPA|/l, r/}} are apical alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|l|l̺}}, {{IPA link|r|r̺}}]}}.{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|pp=78–79}} ** {{IPA|/l/}} is either neutral {{IPAblink|l}} or velarized {{IPAblink|ɫ}}.{{sfnp|Kráľ|1988|p=80}} ** Short {{IPA|/r/}} is most often a tap {{IPAblink|ɾ}}.{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}} * Postalveolar {{IPA|/t͡ʃ, d͡ʒ, ʃ, ʒ/}} are often pronounced hard, i.e. as laminal retroflex (flat postalveolar) {{IPA|[{{IPA link|t͡ʂ}}, {{IPA link|d͡ʐ}}, {{IPA link|ʂ}}, {{IPA link|ʐ}}]}},{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}} as in [[Russian language|Russian]] and [[Polish language|Polish]]. ** {{IPA|/d͡ʒ/}} occurs mainly in loanwords.{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}} * {{IPA|/v/}} is realized as: ** Voiced fricative {{IPAblink|v}} in onsets before voiced obstruents;{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}} ** Voiceless fricative {{IPAblink|f}} in onsets before voiceless obstruents;{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|pp=374, 376}} ** Variably as an approximant {{IPAblink|ʋ}} or a glide {{IPA|[ʊ̯]}} in [[Syllable#Coda|coda]];{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}} ** Approximant {{IPAblink|ʋ}} in all other cases.{{sfnp|Hanulíková|Hamann|2010|p=374}} * {{IPA|/j/}} is an approximant, either palatal or alveolo-palatal.{{sfnp|Recasens|2013|p=15}} Between close front vowels, it can be realized as a fricative {{IPAblink|ʝ}}, whereas between open central vowels, it can be a quite lax approximant {{IPA|[j˕]}}.{{sfnp|Pavlík|2004|p=106}}
Some additional notes includes the following (transcriptions in IPA unless otherwise stated): * {{IPA|/r, l/}} can be syllabic: {{IPA|/r̩, l̩/}}. When they are long (indicated in the spelling with the acute accent: '''ŕ''' and '''ĺ'''), they are always syllabic, e.g. ''vlk'' (wolf), ''prst'' (finger), ''štvrť'' (quarter), ''krk'' (neck), bisyllabic ''vĺča''—''vĺ-ča'' (wolfling), ''vŕba''—''vŕ-ba'' (willow-tree), etc. * {{IPA|/m/}} has the allophone {{IPA|[ɱ]}} in front of the labiodental fricatives {{IPA|/f/}} and {{IPA|/v/}}. * {{IPA|/n/}} in front of (post)alveolar fricatives has a postalveolar allophone {{IPA|[n̠]}}. * {{IPA|/n/}} can be {{IPA|[ŋ]}} in front of the velar plosives {{IPA|/k/}} and {{IPA|/ɡ/}}.
==Stress== {{unreferenced section|date=April 2015}} In the standard language, the [[stress (linguistics)|stress]] is always on the first syllable of a word (or on the preceding preposition, see below). This is not the case in certain dialects. Eastern dialects have penultimate stress (as in [[Polish phonology|Polish]]), which at times makes them difficult to understand for speakers of standard Slovak. Some of the north-central dialects have a weak stress on the first syllable, which becomes stronger and moves to the penultimate in certain cases. Monosyllabic conjunctions, monosyllabic short personal pronouns and auxiliary verb forms of the verb ''byť'' (to be) are usually unstressed.
[[Preposition]]s form a single [[Prosody (linguistics)|prosodic]] unit with the following word, unless the word is long (four syllables or more) or the preposition stands at the beginning of a sentence.
==Official transcriptions== {{unreferenced section|date=April 2015}} Slovak linguists do not usually use IPA for phonetic transcription of their own language or others, but have their own system based on the Slovak alphabet. Many English language textbooks make use of this alternative transcription system. In the following table, pronunciation of each grapheme is given in this system as well as in the IPA.
{|class="wikitable" ! grapheme !! IPA !! transcr. !! example |- | a || {{IPA|/a/}} || a || m'''a'''m'''a''' ('mother') |- | á || {{IPA|/aː/}} || á || l'''á'''ska ('love') |- | ä || {{IPA|/æ/}} || a, e, ä || m'''ä'''so ('meat, flesh') |- | b || {{IPA|/b/}} || b || '''b'''rat ('brother') |- | c || {{IPA|/t͡s/}} || c || '''c'''ukor ('sugar') |- | č || {{IPA|/t͡ʃ/}} || č || '''č'''aj ('tea') |- | d || {{IPA|/d/}} || d || '''d'''om ('house') |- | ď || {{IPA|/ɟ/}} || ď || '''ď'''akovať ('to thank') |- | dz || {{IPA|/d͡z/}} || ʒ || bryn'''dz'''a ('sheep cheese') |- | dž || {{IPA|/d͡ʒ/}} || ǯ || '''dž'''em ('jam') |- | e || {{IPA|/ɛ/}} || e || m'''e'''no ('name') |- | é || {{IPA|/ɛː/}} || é || baz'''é'''n ('pool') |- | f || {{IPA|/f/}} || f || '''f'''arba ('colour') |- | g || {{IPA|/ɡ/}} || g || e'''g'''reš ('gooseberry') |- | h || {{IPA|/ɦ/}} || h || '''h'''lava ('head') |- | ch || {{IPA|/x/}} || x || '''ch'''lieb ('bread') |- | i || {{IPA|/i/}} || i || p'''i'''vo ('beer') |- | í || {{IPA|/iː/}} || í || gomb'''í'''k ('button') |- | j || {{IPA|/j/}} || j || '''j'''ahoda ('strawberry') |- | k || {{IPA|/k/}} || k || '''k'''niha ('book') |- | l || {{IPA|/l/, /l̩/}} || l || p'''l'''ot ('fence') |- | ĺ || {{IPA|/l̩ː/}} || ĺ || m'''ĺ'''kvy ('prone to silence') {{Audio-IPA|SK-mlkvy.ogg|[ˈml̩ːkʋi]}} |- | ľ || {{IPA|/ʎ/}} || ľ || mo'''ľ'''a ('clothes moth') {{Audio-IPA|SK-mola.ogg|[ˈmɔʎa]}} |- | m || {{IPA|/m/}} || m || po'''m'''oc ('''n.'' help') |- | n || {{IPA|/n/}} || n || '''n'''os ('nose') |- | ň || {{IPA|/ɲ/}} || ň || stud'''ň'''a ('''n.'' well') |- | o || {{IPA|/ɔ/}} || o || k'''o'''st'''o'''l ('church') |- | ó || {{IPA|/ɔː/}} || ó || bal'''ó'''n ('balloon') |- | ô || {{IPA|/ʊ̯ɔ/}} || ŭo || k'''ô'''ň ('horse') {{Audio-IPA|SK-kon.ogg|[ˈkʊ̯ɔɲ]}} |- | p || {{IPA|/p/}} || p || lo'''p'''ta ('ball') |- | q || {{IPA|/kv/}} || kv || |- | r || {{IPA|/r/, /r̩/}} || r || mo'''r'''e ('sea') |- | ŕ || {{IPA|/r̩ː/}} || ŕ || v'''ŕ'''ba ('willow tree') |- | s || {{IPA|/s/}} || s || '''s'''t